1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,760
 So now we're going to do more than just console.log

2
00:00:02,760 --> 00:00:04,720
 so we can see what's going on in JavaScript,

3
00:00:04,720 --> 00:00:07,480
 but we're actually going to do modifying the document object

4
00:00:07,480 --> 00:00:09,120
 model in JavaScript.

5
00:00:09,120 --> 00:00:13,320
 So recall on the o1noscript.htm that I just

6
00:00:13,320 --> 00:00:17,800
 used the debugger to modify the document object model, right?

7
00:00:17,800 --> 00:00:19,560
 We modify the document object model,

8
00:00:19,560 --> 00:00:21,720
 and if it's visible through the window,

9
00:00:21,720 --> 00:00:24,600
 then what we changed is instantly changed.

10
00:00:24,600 --> 00:00:26,640
 So literally, we're running JavaScript on one end,

11
00:00:26,640 --> 00:00:28,200
 and the UI just changes.

12
00:00:28,200 --> 00:00:29,640
 It's like it instantaneously.

13
00:00:29,640 --> 00:00:32,760
 Although, if you make mistakes and you

14
00:00:32,760 --> 00:00:35,040
 run code that runs too long, those changes

15
00:00:35,040 --> 00:00:38,120
 will be delayed because we have to finish the JavaScript code

16
00:00:38,120 --> 00:00:40,320
 and let the browser do the redisplay.

17
00:00:40,320 --> 00:00:43,000
 But we can change these by hand, but let's just

18
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:45,200
 do this instead with a trigger.

19
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:48,080
 And to trigger it, we have to be able to grab bits of the DOM

20
00:00:48,080 --> 00:00:50,040
 or query the document object model.

21
00:00:50,040 --> 00:00:54,120
 Let's recall o3event.htm, and all we're showing here

22
00:00:54,120 --> 00:00:57,120
 is that we can define a function in JavaScript,

23
00:00:57,120 --> 00:01:00,480
 then we can have an onClick method that calls my function

24
00:01:00,480 --> 00:01:02,080
 after the click happens.

25
00:01:02,080 --> 00:01:02,920
 Again, remember that.

26
00:01:02,920 --> 00:01:04,440
 Those quotes are important.

27
00:01:04,440 --> 00:01:07,920
 onClick attribute is a string, which

28
00:01:07,920 --> 00:01:10,440
 is only parsed at the moment that you click it,

29
00:01:10,440 --> 00:01:13,960
 and then func is called in that moment.

30
00:01:13,960 --> 00:01:16,040
 So let's do something a little more interesting

31
00:01:16,040 --> 00:01:17,840
 in that onClick method.

32
00:01:17,840 --> 00:01:22,200
 So the top part is still an ID tag, an h1,

33
00:01:22,200 --> 00:01:24,120
 except now we put id equals fun.

34
00:01:24,120 --> 00:01:26,400
 And you can choose anything you want for the ID.

35
00:01:26,400 --> 00:01:28,440
 It's got to be unique across the whole document.

36
00:01:28,440 --> 00:01:29,680
 Remember CSS.

37
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:33,000
 And then it has a bunch of attributes and methods.

38
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:34,520
 Elements have attributes and methods,

39
00:01:34,520 --> 00:01:37,400
 and one of them is innerHTML.

40
00:01:37,400 --> 00:01:42,720
 And I simply assign the innerHTML to a cool header.

41
00:01:42,720 --> 00:01:45,440
 And that's how you basically see that change.

42
00:01:45,440 --> 00:01:46,840
 We're changing the element.

43
00:01:46,840 --> 00:01:50,200
 Now, an important part of this is the function ends,

44
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:51,680
 so it goes back into the browser,

45
00:01:51,680 --> 00:01:54,120
 and the browser sees the change to the document object model

46
00:01:54,120 --> 00:01:55,120
 and then displays it.

47
00:01:55,120 --> 00:01:58,640
 If we did something crazy in the last line of my func

48
00:01:58,640 --> 00:02:03,480
 that did not give the thread back to the browser,

49
00:02:03,480 --> 00:02:04,520
 it might get messed up.

50
00:02:04,520 --> 00:02:06,260
 But we're going to just return.

51
00:02:06,260 --> 00:02:08,720
 We're going to make our change to the document object model.

52
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:12,360
 This code here, console.log let lm equals console.log

53
00:02:12,360 --> 00:02:13,320
 lm innerHTML.

54
00:02:13,320 --> 00:02:14,640
 That's really quick.

55
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:17,040
 Just in a blink of an eye, that code runs,

56
00:02:17,040 --> 00:02:18,960
 meaning there's nothing slow in it.

57
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:20,120
 Everything happens fast.

58
00:02:20,120 --> 00:02:21,560
 There's nothing to wait for.

59
00:02:21,560 --> 00:02:22,920
 So everything happens fast.

60
00:02:22,920 --> 00:02:26,160
 We get the browser back to redisplay things.

61
00:02:26,160 --> 00:02:28,560
 And so you can see, when you click on it,

62
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:30,400
 you can see that it says, I was clicked.

63
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:31,960
 It goes and looks the element up.

64
00:02:31,960 --> 00:02:34,880
 And it says, oh, I just found an h1 tag.

65
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:39,000
 And then I set its innerHTML to be a cool header.

66
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,600
 I could have appended something because I could have read

67
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:43,440
 innerHTML if I felt like it.

68
00:02:43,440 --> 00:02:46,600
 But then as soon as that function finishes,

69
00:02:46,600 --> 00:02:48,720
 then the browser takes over and then

70
00:02:48,720 --> 00:02:50,840
 redisplays the updated DOM.

71
00:02:50,840 --> 00:02:52,280
 And again, everything that we did

72
00:02:52,280 --> 00:02:57,240
 happens so rapidly that you don't even notice it.

73
00:02:57,240 --> 00:02:59,520
 So now let's add some stuff to the DOM.

74
00:02:59,520 --> 00:03:03,000
 We can completely build a tag.

75
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:04,560
 And we can add it to the DOM.

76
00:03:04,560 --> 00:03:07,080
 Everything we've done so far is find a tag, mess with it,

77
00:03:07,080 --> 00:03:08,440
 and then put it back.

78
00:03:08,440 --> 00:03:10,040
 So let's add something to the DOM.

79
00:03:10,040 --> 00:03:14,280
 This is a little bit more intricate.

80
00:03:14,280 --> 00:03:19,640
 But we are going-- and this is a source code, 09-append.htm,

81
00:03:19,640 --> 00:03:21,560
 if you want to go play with it.

82
00:03:21,560 --> 00:03:24,840
 So we're going to have a little button, an anchor tag.

83
00:03:24,840 --> 00:03:27,640
 And we're going to have an add, call the add function.

84
00:03:27,640 --> 00:03:29,880
 And then what you'll notice is we have a ul tag.

85
00:03:29,880 --> 00:03:33,400
 And I've got an ID of zap on the ul tag.

86
00:03:33,400 --> 00:03:38,960
 And then the first item is li, list item tag, and then slash ul.

87
00:03:38,960 --> 00:03:41,960
 And then in the JavaScript, I create a global variable

88
00:03:41,960 --> 00:03:44,520
 called counter equals 1.

89
00:03:44,520 --> 00:03:46,520
 And then I create a function called add.

90
00:03:46,520 --> 00:03:50,000
 And in that function, I go create a new create element,

91
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:53,800
 document.createElement says make me a new element.

92
00:03:53,800 --> 00:03:58,320
 I want an element of a tag, an li tag.

93
00:03:58,320 --> 00:03:59,720
 And then I can set things.

94
00:03:59,720 --> 00:04:01,800
 I can set its class name.

95
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:03,520
 I can set its inner HTML.

96
00:04:03,520 --> 00:04:05,640
 I'm concatenating the word the counter is.

97
00:04:05,640 --> 00:04:07,800
 And then I'm concatenating the number.

98
00:04:07,800 --> 00:04:13,920
 And then I'm going to go document get element ID zap.

99
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:17,360
 Now that is the ul tag, append child.

100
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:20,200
 So the li tag is a child of the ul tag.

101
00:04:20,200 --> 00:04:21,560
 And by saying append child, I say,

102
00:04:21,560 --> 00:04:24,520
 I want to make a new child of this ul tag.

103
00:04:24,520 --> 00:04:28,320
 And so that's when you click it, and then counter goes up by 1.

104
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:29,560
 And it's a global variable.

105
00:04:29,560 --> 00:04:33,560
 So every time we call add, that counter goes up.

106
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:36,000
 So first item, you click it, it says the counter is 1.

107
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:37,640
 You click it again, it adds counter is 2.

108
00:04:37,640 --> 00:04:38,800
 Click it again, add counter is 3.

109
00:04:38,800 --> 00:04:40,600
 You can do this as many times you like.

110
00:04:40,600 --> 00:04:44,200
 But the idea of making a new tag that's

111
00:04:44,200 --> 00:04:45,880
 not connected to the document, we

112
00:04:45,880 --> 00:04:48,780
 make an li tag, we set some stuff in it,

113
00:04:48,780 --> 00:04:51,880
 and then we plug it into the document with append child.

114
00:04:51,880 --> 00:04:53,320
 If you look at the--

115
00:04:53,320 --> 00:04:55,280
 it starts out with first item.

116
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:58,600
 And you'll notice, of course, that the more button

117
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:00,240
 has an event associated with it.

118
00:05:00,240 --> 00:05:03,800
 We created that event with the onclick.

119
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:06,480
 And then after we click it a couple times, boom, boom, boom,

120
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:08,400
 it just adds those things.

121
00:05:08,400 --> 00:05:11,200
 So we can manipulate many things in the document object model

122
00:05:11,200 --> 00:05:14,000
 from JavaScript, including changing the CSS, which

123
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,600
 means we can alter the look of things.

124
00:05:17,600 --> 00:05:22,480
 And so in this, we've got a header tag with an idea fun.

125
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:26,600
 Again, the idea is a way for us to grab it in JavaScript.

126
00:05:26,600 --> 00:05:29,320
 And then we're going to have a button with an idea poof

127
00:05:29,320 --> 00:05:34,520
 and a button, an idea show that has the text hide and show.

128
00:05:34,520 --> 00:05:37,440
 And we're going to do this using add event listener.

129
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:38,760
 They are shorter.

130
00:05:38,760 --> 00:05:39,920
 We could use the onclick.

131
00:05:39,920 --> 00:05:42,000
 But I just want to kind of get used to the notion

132
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:45,800
 that one of the things you do toward the end of your document

133
00:05:45,800 --> 00:05:47,640
 is you add all the event listeners.

134
00:05:47,640 --> 00:05:49,600
 So you have all the HTML that gets displayed.

135
00:05:49,600 --> 00:05:53,080
 And then after that, you add event listeners.

136
00:05:53,080 --> 00:05:56,560
 And so in that script, we do document, getElement, id, show.

137
00:05:56,560 --> 00:05:58,920
 And then we're going to add an event listener.

138
00:05:58,920 --> 00:06:00,720
 And we're looking for the click event.

139
00:06:00,720 --> 00:06:05,200
 And it says, open paren, quote, click, quote, comma.

140
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:08,720
 And then what I have is literally code.

141
00:06:08,720 --> 00:06:10,680
 And again, first class functions.

142
00:06:10,680 --> 00:06:13,440
 The function keyword returns code

143
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:16,920
 so that we are doing the second parameter

144
00:06:16,920 --> 00:06:19,480
 to add event listener.

145
00:06:19,480 --> 00:06:20,680
 So we're creating a function.

146
00:06:20,680 --> 00:06:23,560
 But you'll notice the function currently has no parameters.

147
00:06:23,560 --> 00:06:24,640
 And it has no name.

148
00:06:24,640 --> 00:06:25,440
 Open curly brace.

149
00:06:25,440 --> 00:06:26,920
 It's an anonymous function.

150
00:06:26,920 --> 00:06:28,280
 And it only has one line of code.

151
00:06:28,280 --> 00:06:31,360
 Document, getElement, id, fun.style.

152
00:06:31,360 --> 00:06:33,680
 That's how we get our hands on the CSS.

153
00:06:33,680 --> 00:06:36,600
 Display is a CSS value.

154
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:38,960
 And we're going to set it to the string block.

155
00:06:38,960 --> 00:06:41,200
 So that is our show.

156
00:06:41,200 --> 00:06:43,680
 And we'll see that when we do the poof, the add event

157
00:06:43,680 --> 00:06:47,080
 listener, on the hide button, we're

158
00:06:47,080 --> 00:06:49,860
 going to have an event listener for clicking.

159
00:06:49,860 --> 00:06:52,240
 And in this one, we're going to set the display none, which

160
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:53,360
 means it's going to hide.

161
00:06:53,360 --> 00:06:55,040
 So you click on hide.

162
00:06:55,040 --> 00:06:56,960
 But you'll see a slightly different syntax.

163
00:06:56,960 --> 00:07:01,360
 And you'll see this syntax a lot because that early JavaScript,

164
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:03,160
 there was only one syntax for this.

165
00:07:03,160 --> 00:07:05,800
 And now there's sort of more clever syntaxes

166
00:07:05,800 --> 00:07:07,520
 in later versions of JavaScript.

167
00:07:07,520 --> 00:07:12,640
 And a key thing to remember is that this second example

168
00:07:12,640 --> 00:07:18,320
 for the poof, open paren element, equals greater than,

169
00:07:18,320 --> 00:07:19,920
 which is kind of like a right arrow,

170
00:07:19,920 --> 00:07:22,680
 equals document, getElement, id, fun.

171
00:07:22,680 --> 00:07:26,080
 This is a shortcut to define a function,

172
00:07:26,080 --> 00:07:28,200
 define a function with no name.

173
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:30,140
 And so for all intents and purposes,

174
00:07:30,140 --> 00:07:34,360
 these two bits of code are equivalent.

175
00:07:34,360 --> 00:07:39,720
 We're saying when there is a click on the poof item,

176
00:07:39,720 --> 00:07:42,680
 we're going to call this function that has no name,

177
00:07:42,680 --> 00:07:44,440
 but it takes as one parameter of the event.

178
00:07:44,440 --> 00:07:48,400
 The event is a parameter to all these little events

179
00:07:48,400 --> 00:07:50,360
 that the browser sets up when it calls us.

180
00:07:50,360 --> 00:07:52,160
 And then we're not going to use it, actually.

181
00:07:52,160 --> 00:07:54,200
 We just say document, getElement, id, fun,

182
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:59,200
 style.display equals none, which makes it vanish.

183
00:07:59,200 --> 00:08:03,840
 So if you run this, 13-css.htm, you click on hide.

184
00:08:03,840 --> 00:08:04,760
 The header goes away.

185
00:08:04,760 --> 00:08:06,440
 You click on show, it comes back.

186
00:08:06,440 --> 00:08:08,680
 You click on hide, it goes away.

187
00:08:08,680 --> 00:08:13,480
 And so this is just an example of how you can modify CSS.

188
